On National Missing Children's Day, the article reflects on the disappearance of six-year-old Etan Patz in 1979 and the subsequent efforts to locate and recover missing children. It emphasizes the need for additional resources and information to address the issue. The article discusses the progress made over the last four decades in raising awareness and acting quickly when a child goes missing. It highlights the role of technology, such as online reporting platforms and cellphone-based alert systems, in aiding the search for missing children. The article also mentions the work of the National Center for Missing and Exploited Children (NCMEC) and the recent signing of the Missing Children's Assistance Act of 2018, which extends funding for NCMEC and integrates advanced technology and research into child protection programs. The article concludes by expressing determination to continue the search for missing children and support for the families affected.